{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **JWT validation bypassed when `Authorization` header is absent**

The guard `if let Some(auth_header) = ...` means any request that omits the `Authorization` header completely skips JWT validation and flows directly through to the shared-secret verifier. Legitimate Teams Bot Framework requests always include a `Bearer` token; omitting the header is exactly what a forged request would do.

When no `webhook_secret` is configured (which is explicitly optional in the config template), the shared-secret verifier adds no additional protection, so this becomes a full authentication bypass.

The validator should be fetched first, and if it is present, a missing `Authorization` header must be treated as an authentication failure:

```rust
// Resolve JWT validator for this account.
let jwt_validator = {
    let plugin = teams_plugin.read().await;
    plugin.jwt_validator(&account_id)
};
// If JWT is configured, the header is required and must be valid.
if let Some(validator) = jwt_validator {
    let header_str = headers
        .get("authorization")
        .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok())
        .unwrap_or("");
    if !validator.validate(header_str).await {
        return (
            StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED,
            Json(serde_json::json!({ "ok": false, "error": "invalid JWT" })),
        )
            .into_response();
    }
}
```","id":3016772332,"line":null,"path":"crates/httpd/src/server.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **`update_activity` silently swallows HTTP errors, masking failures to callers**

When the PUT request returns a 4xx or 5xx status, the function logs at `debug!` level and then returns `Ok(())`. Every caller that needs to know whether the edit succeeded (primarily `edit_message`, which is the implementation backing the `teams_edit_message` agent tool) will always receive a success result, even when the server-side edit actually failed.

Concretely, `TeamsEditMessageTool::execute` calls:
```rust
p.edit_message(&account_id, chat_id, activity_id, text).await
    .map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!("{e}"))?;
Ok(json!({ "ok": true, "action": "edit" }))
```
…and will report `{"ok": true}` to the agent even when the message was never updated.

The streaming use-case intentionally ignores edit errors (which is fine — the `let _ = self.update_activity(...).await` calls in `send_stream_edit_in_place` already discard errors). The fix is to propagate the HTTP error in `update_activity` so that explicit callers like `edit_message` can surface it:

```rust
if !resp.status().is_success() {
    let status = resp.status();
    let body = resp.text().await.unwrap_or_default();
    return Err(ChannelError::external(
        "Teams activity update failed",
        std::io::Error::other(format!("{status}: {body}")),
    ));
}
```

The `send_stream_edit_in_place` callers already discard the `Result` with `let _ = ...`, so they are unaffected by this change.","id":3016772414,"line":218,"path":"crates/msteams/src/outbound.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P2" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p2.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **JWKS cache expiry during endpoint outage rejects all legitimate requests**

When the cache TTL expires and `fetch_jwks` fails (network hiccup, Microsoft outage), `get_or_fetch_jwks` returns `None`. `try_validate_with_jwks` then returns `None` (key not found), and `validate` returns `false`, which causes the webhook handler to return a 401 to Microsoft's Bot Framework — which will then retry, causing a retry storm.

The standard pattern is to continue using the stale (but still cryptographically valid) key set until a fresh fetch succeeds. Consider keeping the stale `CachedJwks` available in the error path:

```rust
// On fetch failure, fall back to stale cache if available.
let mut guard = cache.write().await;
if let Some(cached) = guard.as_ref() {
    warn!("JWKS refresh failed, using stale cache: {e}");
    return Some(Arc::new(cached.keys.clone()));
}
return None;
```","id":3016772476,"line":193,"path":"crates/msteams/src/jwt.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P2" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p2.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **`welcomed_conversations` is not persisted across restarts**

The `HashSet<String>` is initialized empty every time an account is registered (on every gateway start). After a restart, the bot will re-send welcome cards to every conversation that messages it, including users who have already received one. For low-traffic bots this is mainly a UX annoyance; for high-traffic bots it could be noticeable.

Consider persisting this set alongside other durable state, or at minimum noting this limitation in the config documentation so operators aren't surprised.","id":3016772808,"line":30,"path":"crates/msteams/src/state.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **Bot Framework token used for Graph API calls**

`graph_client()` calls `get_access_token()`, which acquires an OAuth token with `config.oauth_scope` — defaulting to `"https://api.botframework.com/.default"`. This token's audience is the Bot Connector Service, not Microsoft Graph.

Microsoft Graph (`https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0` and `/beta`) requires a token scoped to `"https://graph.microsoft.com/.default"`. Sending a Bot Framework token to Graph results in a `401 Unauthorized` from Azure AD.

This means every Graph API call made through `graph_client()` will fail in production, including:
- All five agent tools (`teams_search_messages`, `teams_member_info`, `teams_pin_message`, `teams_edit_message`, `teams_read_message`)
- Reactions (`add_reaction`, `remove_reaction`, `list_reactions` in `outbound.rs`)

The fix is to acquire a separate token for Graph API calls with the `https://graph.microsoft.com/.default` scope. One clean approach is to add a dedicated `graph_oauth_scope` config field (defaulting to `"https://graph.microsoft.com/.default"`) and a separate token cache, then use those in `graph_client()` instead of reusing the Bot Framework token/cache.","id":3020550589,"line":141,"path":"crates/msteams/src/plugin.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **OData `$search` URL construction is malformed**

Two issues in the URL built for `search_messages`:

1. **Double-encoding inside OData quotes** — `urlencoding::encode(&sanitized)` percent-encodes the search term and then embeds it inside OData `$search` double-quotes (`$search="hello%20world"`). The Graph API expects the raw search term inside the quotes (`$search="hello world"`), not a percent-encoded value.

2. **Spurious trailing `%20`** — the format string contains a literal `%20` right after the closing `"` of the search term: `$search="{query}"%20&$top=…`. This corrupts the parameter boundary.

Corrected construction:
```rust
let url = format!(
    "{GRAPH_API_BASE}/chats/{}/messages?$search=\"{}\"&$top={top}",
    urlencoding::encode(chat_id),
    sanitized,   // raw, not URL-encoded inside OData quoted string
);
```

The `$filter` append below has the same double-encoding issue.","id":3020550647,"line":242,"path":"crates/msteams/src/graph.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **Wrong OAuth scope used for Graph API in `fetch_thread_messages`**

The credential acquired here is scoped to the Bot Framework connector, not Microsoft Graph. Passing it to `fetch_chat_messages` returns HTTP 401 in any standard app registration — the code comment at line 763 even acknowledges this may fail. `AccountState` already has a separate credential cache for Graph-scoped access (`graph_token_cache`), added when `graph_client()` was fixed, but it isn't used here. The fix is to extract that field and call the Graph-specific auth helper instead.","id":3054349447,"line":null,"path":"crates/msteams/src/plugin.rs"}
{"body":"<a href="#"><img alt="P1" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p1.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **`add_reaction` / `remove_reaction` use wrong credential scope for Graph API**

Both methods acquire Bot Framework–scoped credentials and pass them to the Microsoft Graph reaction endpoints (`setReaction` / `unsetReaction`). Graph requires a different credential audience and returns HTTP 401. `AccountState` already carries a separate Graph-scoped credential cache (`graph_token_cache`) added when `graph_client()` was fixed; both reaction methods should use that field and the Graph-specific auth helper instead.","id":3054349517,"line":665,"path":"crates/msteams/src/outbound.rs"}
